    <node id="1. Local authorities have been heavily involved in discussing and exploring the implications of the Bill. They will continue to be involved in the implementation phase, with a focus on awareness raising, early support, and prevention services for families.&#10;2. There is a commitment from the Welsh Government to full involvement of all relevant parties in the implementation process. This includes a major awareness-raising campaign to ensure that families, carers, and parents understand the changes and are on board with the new culture and value system for children.&#10;3. Support services for early intervention and prevention will be available to parents and carers who may struggle with parenting. These services are intended to be a universal offer across Wales, ensuring that every parent has access to this support.&#10;4. The implementation of the Bill should ideally be done carefully and with the right resources to avoid any unintended consequences. Social services departments, particularly children's social services, are currently overstretched and dealing with high numbers of child harm and neglect cases. It is crucial that resources are made available to support these departments in implementing the new legislation while continuing their work with high-needs children and families.&#10;5. In education settings, the main changes would be around training and awareness to ensure that safeguarding leads within schools have the right training and support. Preventative services for parents will also be emphasized, with schools playing a role in signposting and potentially hosting such programs.&#10;6. Social services will continue to work closely with local authorities, families, carers, and parents throughout the implementation process, ensuring that all parties are informed and involved in the changes." />
    <node id=" we need to take families, carers and parents with us on this. Also we need to ensure that there is that support available to parents and carers that do sometimes struggle with parenting, and that needs to be a universal offer across Wales. If we're to progress with this, that has to be an option that is offered to every parent in Wales.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Sally Jenkins&#10;Content: Local authorities have already been very heavily involved in terms of looking at this Bill and exploring what the issues are and the discussions and looking at what the implications from a local authority perspective will be, as Huw describes, both in terms of the awareness raising, early support and intervention and prevention services for families against the backdrop of the current issues that we have in local government, but also awareness raising—because absolutely it is key that families come with us on this journey. This is not an imposition. This is embracing a culture and a value system for our children.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. I've got some questions now from Dawn Bowden on the implementation of the Bill.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: Thank" />
