    <node id="The various factors that have contributed to the rise in the numbers of looked-after children in Wales and England include increased austerity, which has led to reduced funding for children's services and support programs. Additionally, there has been an increased awareness of adverse childhood experiences (ACEs) in Wales, leading to a better understanding of the impact of factors such as domestic abuse on children and a greater emphasis on their protection. Changes in practice with judiciary colleagues and the police service, as well as changes in preventative services, have also contributed to this rise. These factors, combined with a huge amount of work being done across local authorities and Welsh Government to address and understand the issue, aim to reduce the number of children coming into care while improving outcomes for those who are already in care." />
    <node id=" give you more work to do in those areas.&#10;Speaker: Sally Jenkins&#10;Content: On the reasons for the rise in the numbers of looked-after children in Wales, which are higher than those in England, and also the numbers of contacts that we have across the local authorities, the work of the care crisis review, which was completed last year; the work of Isabelle Trowler, who's the chief social worker in England; countless research and reports that have taken place in the last 18 months; and currently the public law working group, under the auspices of the president of the family court, would all indicate that it's multifactorial. So, what you have is a range of reasons that have led to the increasing numbers of children becoming looked after across England and Wales. What you can't do is identify a single reason. There have been headlines that have said, 'Is it increased austerity?' That is clearly a part of this. Is it in Wales an increased awareness of adverse childhood experiences and the emphasis of the impact on children of, for example, domestic abuse? Is it because of our understanding of what happens to children in those households? All of that research would say it's all of those things. And then, when you also add" />
    <node id=" that are experiencing significant problems, but who we want to support through our early intervention and prevention programmes, and that is why it is important that there is investment in those programmes, so that children do not end up in that terrible position where we have to, for their safety, take them from their birth families to protect them. And the reality is, in Wales, that we are doing that to more children than we've done for a long time, and the numbers are growing across Wales. And that is only because of the most appalling neglect and abuse, because there is no way that any judge would permit us to act to make a child safe if it was not for that fact, and the facts are there. So, I don't want that focus to be lost, but, of course, we welcome and understand the need to progress this piece of legislation.&#10;Speaker: Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: That rise that you talk about here, is that due to more interventions, greater awareness, more incidents? I'm trying to link this to the Bill in terms of whether the Bill is actually going to give you more work to do in those areas.&#10;Speaker: Sally Jenkins&#10;Content: On the reasons for the rise in the numbers of looked-after" />
    <node id="Based on the transcript, Alastair Birch expressed confidence that teachers and other educational professionals would be clear about their duty to support the implementation of the Bill. He mentioned that the training requirements for all professionals in education settings are clear, with a universal tier 1 training that emphasizes the duty to report. He also noted that 'Keeping learners safe', which serves as the bible for education professionals, stresses the responsibility on the professional to make referrals and for that universal service.&#10;&#10;However, Alastair Birch also acknowledged the need for clarity in terms of making sure that safeguarding leads within all schools have the right training and support. He mentioned the necessity of working closely with social care colleagues and other services like housing and education to ensure effective implementation.&#10;&#10;Regarding the thresholds for social care and the responsibility to make referrals, Alastair Birch emphasized that if a professional believes there is significant harm to a child, they are under a duty to report it to social care. He acknowledged the importance of maintaining trust while fulfilling this duty, noting that most referrals are made with parental consent and that professionals need to work together to ensure the best outcomes for children and families." />
    <node id="1. Potential risks and concerns include:&#10;   a) Increased referrals might cause potential harm to relationships and create mistrust between educators and parents.&#10;   b) There is a risk of criminalizing parents, which could lead to further strain on families already facing significant challenges.&#10;   c) Overstretched social services departments may struggle to handle the increased number of referrals effectively.&#10;&#10;2. Mitigation strategies include:&#10;   a) Ensuring that professionals are aware of their responsibilities and feel confident in making necessary referrals when significant harm or neglect is suspected, while also building trust with parents by working daily to engage and support families.&#10;   b) Providing early intervention and prevention services for families who may struggle with parenting, encouraging a universal offer across Wales so that every parent has access to this support.&#10;   c) Launching campaigns to inform vulnerable children about resources like Childline, where they can seek help and ask questions about what constitutes acceptable behavior towards them.&#10;   d) Making local authorities, social services, and the Welsh Government fully involved in the implementation process with a major awareness-raising campaign to ensure that families, carers, and parents understand the changes and are on board with the new culture and value system for children.&#10;   e) Ensuring that resources are made available to support social services departments in implementing the new legislation while continuing their work with high-needs children and families.&#10;   f) Focusing on training and awareness within education settings to ensure that safeguarding leads have the right training and support, and working closely with social care colleagues and other services like housing and education to ensure effective implementation." />
    <node id="The speaker, Sally Jenkins, believes that the purpose of the increased clarity in training for various professions related to child protection, safeguarding, adverse childhood experiences, and trauma-informed approach is to create a clear message for all professionals working with children. She emphasizes that this is not about leveraging additional money for social services but a commitment to the rights of children in Wales. The training aims to empower educational professionals, who are already highly trained and aware of ACE and trauma, by focusing on and increasing their understanding of particular issues related to adverse childhood experiences.&#10;&#10;Sally Jenkins also mentions that there could be positive unintended consequences, such as reinvigorating discussions around the voice of the child within various contexts. She does not think that this Bill is a way of getting money into social services; instead, it is about reinforcing the commitment to children's rights and promoting their well-being in Wales." />
    <node id=": Sally Jenkins&#10;Content: No. And I agree with that—that there clearly are—but if you think, many of those things will be aligned with work we are already doing, but it brings a clarity to that work. So, our teachers, our social workers, our health workers, our police officers already get substantial training around child protection, around safeguarding, around adverse childhood experiences and around a trauma-informed approach to children. What this does is it layers a clarity on that. But rather than having a part of that training, which has to deal with this as an aspect—that is no longer there; it is a clear message for all professions.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: I fully appreciate that, and in the briefing note you've given us, you've outlined the pressures on social services. So, do you think this is another way of getting money into social services?&#10;Speaker: Sally Jenkins&#10;Content: If this was a way of getting money into—. I can think of better ways, but I don't think this is it. No, I mean, I absolutely do not think that. I think this is a clear commitment to the rights of children in Wales; this is not about levering additional" />
    <node id="1. The transcript suggests that there may not be sufficient resources and services like Families First in local governments to prevent harm and support families, as speakers have expressed concerns about increased pressures on social services and reductions in funding for children's services. It is crucial to invest more in prevention programs, as early intervention can help address issues before they escalate and require more intensive (and costly) interventions.&#10;2. To mitigate these concerns, it is recommended to provide local authorities with the necessary resources to effectively implement new legislation and support social services departments. This includes early intervention and prevention services for families facing significant challenges, as well as awareness-raising campaigns to inform vulnerable children about available resources like Childline.&#10;3. Additionally, training and awareness within education settings should be prioritized to ensure that safeguarding leads have the right support and resources. Schools can also play a role in signposting parents to preventative services and potentially hosting such programs.&#10;4. To ensure successful implementation of new policies and legislation, it is essential to involve local authorities, social services, the Welsh Government, families, carers, and parents in the process. A major awareness-raising campaign can help ensure that all parties understand the changes and are on board with the new culture and value system for children." />
