    <node id="1. Over the first six months to a year, costs related to the implementation of the proposed legislation are expected to rise due to increased awareness and understanding of the new law. These costs will not only come from an increase in referrals but also from additional expenses such as training of staff, awareness-raising efforts, and other related costs.&#10;&#10;2. During this period, local authorities, Welsh Government, social services, police, CAFCASS Cymru, and third-party organizations involved in preventative services will collaborate to ensure successful implementation. They will monitor the number of referrals and cases, associated costs, and ensure that resources are distributed proportionately between agencies involved in implementing the new law.&#10;&#10;3. Some of these related costs may be aligned with existing initiatives, helping offset some expenses. However, significant time and effort will still be required to coordinate efforts across various stakeholders.&#10;&#10;4. As Dawn Bowden AM mentioned, there could be a &quot;double impact&quot; on Wales due to the culture shift brought about by the new legislation – an increase in referrals because of increased awareness and more parents seeking support services. This potential dual effect will need to be considered when evaluating the trajectory of costs during implementation.&#10;&#10;5. Over the first six months and 12 months, ongoing monitoring and assessment will help provide a clearer understanding of these costs as agencies work together to ensure families do not feel criminalized and children's rights are upheld within Welsh society." />
    <node id="1. The proposed Bill aims to clarify how local authorities care for and nurture children in Wales, particularly by protecting them from harm as stated by Huw David. This includes discussing the implications of the Bill on local authorities and potential trajectories for referral into their services.&#10;2. The Bill is grounded in the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child, which enshrines the view that physical punishment and physical harm to a child are forms of harm. It seeks to prevent such harm by supporting parents in raising children without recourse to physical punishment. This reflects a cultural change that has taken place in Wales over the last 30 to 40 years.&#10;3. The Bill is not intended as a way of getting money into social services, but rather about reinforcing the commitment to children's rights and promoting their well-being in Wales. It aims to create clarity in how professionals working with children approach child protection, safeguarding, adverse childhood experiences, and trauma-informed approaches.&#10;4. The Bill is expected to improve children's positions within their families by changing legislation regarding physical punishment, as research has shown that introducing such legislation across the world improves children's situations in their homes. Children find physical punishment emotionally damaging, and this view is clear among children themselves.&#10;5. The Bill aims to ensure that families come with them on this journey, and it emphasizes the need for support available to parents who struggle with parenting as a universal offer across Wales. Local authorities have been heavily involved in exploring the implications of this Bill from various perspectives, including awareness-raising and early support and intervention services for families.&#10;6. By addressing physical punishment as a form of harm, the Bill affects existing local authority responsibilities by requiring them to promote alternative methods of discipline and parenting support, ultimately contributing to a culture and value system that prioritizes children's well-being in Wales." />
