    <node id="1. The disagreement between Sally Jenkins and the children's commissioner/equal protection network revolves around the approach to defining what constitutes corporal punishment in the Bill. On one hand, Sally Jenkins emphasizes the need for greater clarity in the definition of corporal punishment, arguing that it would help address ambiguity in how children are treated and potentially prevent more serious physical or sexual abuse. This clarity, she believes, would contribute to shifting societal attitudes towards recognizing the need for physically safe environments for all children and improve children's positions within their families.&#10;&#10;On the other hand, the children's commissioner and the equal protection network argue for simplicity in the Bill, stating that a simpler approach would make the legislation more accessible and easier to understand for the general public. They likely believe that a simpler definition would encourage more people to report instances of corporal punishment, leading to increased protection for children and better enforcement of the law.&#10;&#10;The disagreement lies in finding the right balance between clarity and simplicity to create a Bill that effectively addresses corporal punishment while also being easily understood by the public." />
