    <edge source=" was a duty in that Act for Ministers to promote transplantation. Surely, that awareness raising aspect would be clearer for everyone if it was on the face of the Bill. Do you have an opinion on that?&#10;Speaker: Huw David&#10;Content: Well, Welsh Government have given that commitment, and I know the Welsh Government honour every commitment that they make—[Laughter.]&#10;Speaker: Sian Gwenllian AM&#10;Content: That's why I'm asking.&#10;Speaker: Huw David&#10;Content: I don't know whether that is necessary—I'm not a legislator. I think that there's obviously an inherent interest in Welsh Government raising awareness, because we have to raise awareness effectively for this to be successful, otherwise we will have parents who feel that they're being criminalised, and that's the last thing we want. I think it's worthy of consideration, but, as I say, I'm not a legislator or a lawyer, so I don't know what implications that will have long term. But to be fair to Welsh Government, I think that commitment is one that I'm sure will be honoured, because Welsh Government will want to make a success of this Bill if it does receive Royal Assent.&#10;Speaker" target="1. Sally Jenkins does not believe it is essential for specific details to be included in the text of the Bill, instead advocating for discussions on nuancing during the implementation phase. She emphasizes the importance of simplicity and clarity to avoid further confusion.&#10;&#10;2. Huw David supports full involvement of all relevant parties in the implementation process, with a commitment from the Welsh Government to ensure there is an effective awareness-raising campaign and support available for parents and carers. He believes that families should be taken along on this journey and not feel criminalized.&#10;&#10;3. Alastair Birch thinks it would be beneficial for clarity and training purposes to have the requirement for safeguarding leads within schools to have proper training and support included in the Bill. However, he doesn't explicitly express an opinion on whether it should be on the face of the Bill.&#10;&#10;4. Sian Gwenllian AM questions why the Welsh Government is hesitant to include a clear duty for Ministers to raise awareness about the impact of the Bill, as was done with the Human Transplantation (Wales) Act 2013. She believes this would make it clearer for everyone involved.&#10;&#10;5. Huw David acknowledges Sian Gwenllian AM's question and confirms that there is a commitment from the Welsh Government to honor their commitments regarding awareness-raising campaigns and support for families, carers, and parents during the implementation phase. He also mentions it would be worth considering having such a duty included in the Bill but admits he is not a legislator or lawyer.">
