ussions on nuancing during the implementation phase. She emphasizes the importance of simplicity and clarity to avoid further confusion.&#10;&#10;2. Huw David supports full involvement of all relevant parties in the implementation process, with a commitment from the Welsh Government to ensure there is an effective awareness-raising campaign and support available for parents and carers. He believes that families should be taken along on this journey and not feel criminalized.&#10;&#10;3. Alastair Birch thinks it would be beneficial for clarity and training purposes to have the requirement for safeguarding leads within schools to have proper training and support included in the Bill. However, he doesn't explicitly express an opinion on whether it should be on the face of the Bill.&#10;&#10;4. Sian Gwenllian AM questions why the Welsh Government is hesitant to include a clear duty for Ministers to raise awareness about the impact of the Bill, as was done with the Human Transplantation (Wales) Act 2013. She believes this would make it clearer for everyone involved.&#10;&#10;5. Huw David acknowledges Sian Gwenllian AM's question and confirms that there is a commitment from the Welsh Government to honor their commitments regarding awareness-raising campaigns and support for families, carers, and parents during the implementation phase. He also mentions it would be worth considering having such a duty included in the Bill but admits he is not a legislator or lawyer.">
