    <edge source="1. Local authorities have been heavily involved in discussing and exploring the implications of the Bill. They will continue to be involved in the implementation phase, with a focus on awareness raising, early support, and prevention services for families.&#10;2. There is a commitment from the Welsh Government to full involvement of all relevant parties in the implementation process. This includes a major awareness-raising campaign to ensure that families, carers, and parents understand the changes and are on board with the new culture and value system for children.&#10;3. Support services for early intervention and prevention will be available to parents and carers who may struggle with parenting. These services are intended to be a universal offer across Wales, ensuring that every parent has access to this support.&#10;4. The implementation of the Bill should ideally be done carefully and with the right resources to avoid any unintended consequences. Social services departments, particularly children's social services, are currently overstretched and dealing with high numbers of child harm and neglect cases. It is crucial that resources are made available to support these departments in implementing the new legislation while continuing their work with high-needs children and families.&#10;5. In education settings, the main changes would be around training and awareness to ensure that safeguarding leads within schools have the right training and support. Preventative services for parents will also be emphasized, with schools playing a role in signposting and potentially hosting such programs.&#10;6. Social services will continue to work closely with local authorities, families, carers, and parents throughout the implementation process, ensuring that all parties are informed and involved in the changes." target="1. Potential risks and concerns include:&#10;   a) Increased referrals might cause potential harm to relationships and create mistrust between educators and parents.&#10;   b) There is a risk of criminalizing parents, which could lead to further strain on families already facing significant challenges.&#10;   c) Overstretched social services departments may struggle to handle the increased number of referrals effectively.&#10;&#10;2. Mitigation strategies include:&#10;   a) Ensuring that professionals are aware of their responsibilities and feel confident in making necessary referrals when significant harm or neglect is suspected, while also building trust with parents by working daily to engage and support families.&#10;   b) Providing early intervention and prevention services for families who may struggle with parenting, encouraging a universal offer across Wales so that every parent has access to this support.&#10;   c) Launching campaigns to inform vulnerable children about resources like Childline, where they can seek help and ask questions about what constitutes acceptable behavior towards them.&#10;   d) Making local authorities, social services, and the Welsh Government fully involved in the implementation process with a major awareness-raising campaign to ensure that families, carers, and parents understand the changes and are on board with the new culture and value system for children.&#10;   e) Ensuring that resources are made available to support social services departments in implementing the new legislation while continuing their work with high-needs children and families.&#10;   f) Focusing on training and awareness within education settings to ensure that safeguarding leads have the right training and support, and working closely with social care colleagues and other services like housing and education to ensure effective implementation.">
