m and support families, as speakers have expressed concerns about increased pressures on social services and reductions in funding for children's services. It is crucial to invest more in prevention programs, as early intervention can help address issues before they escalate and require more intensive (and costly) interventions.&#10;2. To mitigate these concerns, it is recommended to provide local authorities with the necessary resources to effectively implement new legislation and support social services departments. This includes early intervention and prevention services for families facing significant challenges, as well as awareness-raising campaigns to inform vulnerable children about available resources like Childline.&#10;3. Additionally, training and awareness within education settings should be prioritized to ensure that safeguarding leads have the right support and resources. Schools can also play a role in signposting parents to preventative services and potentially hosting such programs.&#10;4. To ensure successful implementation of new policies and legislation, it is essential to involve local authorities, social services, the Welsh Government, families, carers, and parents in the process. A major awareness-raising campaign can help ensure that all parties understand the changes and are on board with the new culture and value system for children.">
