    <edge source=": Dawn Bowden AM&#10;Content: So, I've got largely positive feedback from you in terms of the Bill and its intentions, and so on. Do you foresee any unintended consequences for this Bill?&#10;Speaker: Huw David&#10;Content: If we implement it carefully, if we implement it with the right resources, then I hope not. I think not. But as with every piece of legislation, it is about the implementation, it is about the cultural change as well, and that's why I cannot overstress the importance of making sure that resources are made available, because our social services departments—children's social services in particular—are overstretched. They are at breaking point—make no bones about it—and they are dealing with children who are facing serious harm and neglect. We are having record numbers of contacts from police, from teachers, from doctors and, of course, from children themselves who are experiencing that harm and neglect. And obviously, we want to focus our energy and our attention on those children. Equally, though, we don't want to lose sight of those families and children that are experiencing significant problems, but who we want to support through our early intervention and prevention programmes, and that is why it is important that there is investment in" target="1. Determining the threshold for child abuse: The exact threshold for child abuse is not explicitly stated in the transcript, but it is mentioned that if there is a suspicion of significant harm or neglect to the child, a referral should be made to the child care assessment team or the police. This determination is best left to the professionals who have multi-agency awareness and can assess the situation thoroughly.&#10;2. Making parents and vulnerable children aware of the line: While it may not be possible to explicitly define the threshold for everyone, increasing awareness about available support programs and resources can help both parents and vulnerable children. This includes educating professionals in schools to recognize signs of significant harm and make appropriate referrals. For vulnerable children, campaigns should be launched to inform them about resources like Childline, where they can seek help and ask questions about what constitutes acceptable behavior towards them.&#10;3. Preventing criminalization of parents: The speakers emphasize that the aim is not to criminalize parents who are bringing up their children. Instead, support programs should be made available for families facing significant problems, even if they don't meet the threshold for child abuse or neglect intervention. This approach encourages early intervention and prevention efforts while minimizing unnecessary involvement in families' lives.">
