    <edge source=" calling for essential to be on the face of the Bill?&#10;Speaker: Sally Jenkins&#10;Content: It's not essential for it to be on the face of the Bill. What we would like to see is discussion within the implementation phase for that nuancing. Absolutely agree in terms of simplicity—I think that is really important—and I've already mentioned clarity. What we don't want to do is further confuse the position. We know that the legislation in different countries has done that, and there are ways that you can do it, but what we would welcome is an opportunity during the implementation phase for discussion.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. Thank you.&#10;Speaker: Huw David&#10;Content: And, as a principle, obviously we would welcome full involvement, and we know there's the commitment from Welsh Government to full involvement in the implementation, because, as with every piece of legislation, implementation is the most important part, and we would want to ensure there is that commitment to a major awareness-raising campaign, and there is that from Welsh Government, because we need to take families, carers and parents with us on this. Also we need to ensure that there is that support available to parents and carers that" target="1. Sally Jenkins does not believe it is essential for specific details to be included in the text of the Bill, instead advocating for discussions on nuancing during the implementation phase. She emphasizes the importance of simplicity and clarity to avoid further confusion.&#10;&#10;2. Huw David supports full involvement of all relevant parties in the implementation process, with a commitment from the Welsh Government to ensure there is an effective awareness-raising campaign and support available for parents and carers. He believes that families should be taken along on this journey and not feel criminalized.&#10;&#10;3. Alastair Birch thinks it would be beneficial for clarity and training purposes to have the requirement for safeguarding leads within schools to have proper training and support included in the Bill. However, he doesn't explicitly express an opinion on whether it should be on the face of the Bill.&#10;&#10;4. Sian Gwenllian AM questions why the Welsh Government is hesitant to include a clear duty for Ministers to raise awareness about the impact of the Bill, as was done with the Human Transplantation (Wales) Act 2013. She believes this would make it clearer for everyone involved.&#10;&#10;5. Huw David acknowledges Sian Gwenllian AM's question and confirms that there is a commitment from the Welsh Government to honor their commitments regarding awareness-raising campaigns and support for families, carers, and parents during the implementation phase. He also mentions it would be worth considering having such a duty included in the Bill but admits he is not a legislator or lawyer.">
