    <edge source="Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay. Good morning, everyone. Welcome to the Children, Young People and Education Committee. We've received apologies for absence from Suzy Davies and Jack Sargeant and I'm very pleased to welcome Jayne Bryant back, who is substituting for Jack today. Are there any declarations of interest from Members, please? No. Okay, thank you. Item 2, then, this morning, is our sixth scrutiny session on the Children (Abolition of Defence of Reasonable Punishment) (Wales) Bill. I'm very pleased to welcome our witnesses this morning: Sally Jenkins, who is chair of All Wales Heads of Children’s Services and is here representing the Association of Directors of Social Services; Alastair Birch, who is senior system leader for equalities and safeguarding at Pembrokeshire County Council, who is here representing the Association of Directors of Education Wales; and Councillor Huw David, who is the Welsh Local Government Association spokesperson for health and social care and leader of Bridgend County Borough Council. So, thank you all for attending this morning. We're very pleased to have you here. We've got a lot of ground to cover, so, if you" target="1. Dawn Bowden AM, along with other agencies such as Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service Cymru and the police, has been involved in workshops for at least two years, discussing the implications of the Bill on their agencies and potential trajectories for referral into their services. They have also had extensive discussions with CAFCASS Cymru regarding the impact on private law cases and any fallout that could affect children's services, taking into account the pressures these services are already facing. Dawn Bowden AM has been committed to working closely with Welsh Government officials throughout this process and intends to continue doing so.&#10;2. Huw David mentioned that local authorities have been consulted as key stakeholders, and their officials have collaborated with Welsh Government officials to ensure the successful implementation of the Bill, should it be passed.&#10;3. Sally Jenkins, representing the Association of Directors of Social Services, has had involvement in this area for over two years and welcomed the clarity that this Bill would bring, not only for children and parents but also for professionals. She recognizes that although this legislation is infrequently used, its implementation will significantly impact how they care for and nurture children in Wales, providing much-needed clarity. Local authorities have conducted some research to understand the potential impact and related costs, and further work is needed during the implementation phase.">
