    <edge source=" to that. Janet.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Yes. Can you outline the practical ways in which social services' interaction with parents will change as a result of this proposed law and do you envisage that all referrals to the police will be automatically referred to social services for an assessment? Who's going to make those decisions?&#10;Speaker: Sally Jenkins&#10;Content: That will be part of the implementation phase about that decision making. Interestingly, the number of referrals that we currently get from the police that we take absolutely no action on is extraordinary. So, we get a very, very large number of—. It will be happening now; sitting in the civic centre in Newport City Council will be a whole host of social workers taking in the public protection notifications from overnight. It's 10 o'clock, so they're assessing them now, as we speak. And an awful lot of those will have no further action from the local authority.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: But will they be investigated?&#10;Speaker: Sally Jenkins&#10;Content: No. There will be no action. There are countless referrals made by agencies to local authorities that we take no action on.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch" target="1. Concerns about neglect or other general worries: If educational professionals notice general concerns about a child's wellbeing, they may gather this information and make a referral to the Child Care Assessment Team. However, upon assessment, it might be determined that there is no significant harm or neglect taking place.&#10;&#10;2. Combined evidence insufficient for intervention: Sometimes, multiple pieces of information regarding a child's situation are collected but do not meet the threshold for significant harm or neglect when considered together. In such cases, these referrals may result in no further action being taken by local authorities.&#10;&#10;Examples provided by Sally Jenkins in the transcript include situations where there is a paper assessment of referrals and a look at what has happened, who is involved, and what the police have reported. These assessments aim to improve the process between police and social services, ensuring that only incidents requiring action are investigated further.">
