    <edge source=", thank you all for attending this morning. We're very pleased to have you here. We've got a lot of ground to cover, so, if you're happy, we'll go straight into questions and I'll start just by asking about your general support for the Bill, which is outlined in the evidence. Can you just explain why you think the current law is ineffective or unclear?&#10;Speaker: Alastair Birch&#10;Content: Bore da—bore da, bawb. So, I'm Alastair Birch. The statement, really, from ADEW is that the rights of the child should be educated and achieved, really, under the United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child. The current legislation has been criticised, obviously, by the UN concerning the defence of reasonable punishment still being within our current legislation. So, we will always—ADEW will always—advocate that the rights of the child be upheld, so that is really the fundamental aspect in terms of the statement from ADEW, and the position of ADEW is that the rights of the child are fundamental in this process. And there are certain articles—. I know that the Rights of Children and Young Persons (Wales) Measure 2011 made sure that article 3 and article" target="Based on the transcript, Alastair Birch expressed confidence that teachers and other educational professionals would be clear about their duty to support the implementation of the Bill. He mentioned that the training requirements for all professionals in education settings are clear, with a universal tier 1 training that emphasizes the duty to report. He also noted that 'Keeping learners safe', which serves as the bible for education professionals, stresses the responsibility on the professional to make referrals and for that universal service.&#10;&#10;However, Alastair Birch also acknowledged the need for clarity in terms of making sure that safeguarding leads within all schools have the right training and support. He mentioned the necessity of working closely with social care colleagues and other services like housing and education to ensure effective implementation.&#10;&#10;Regarding the thresholds for social care and the responsibility to make referrals, Alastair Birch emphasized that if a professional believes there is significant harm to a child, they are under a duty to report it to social care. He acknowledged the importance of maintaining trust while fulfilling this duty, noting that most referrals are made with parental consent and that professionals need to work together to ensure the best outcomes for children and families.">
