    <edge source=", thank you all for attending this morning. We're very pleased to have you here. We've got a lot of ground to cover, so, if you're happy, we'll go straight into questions and I'll start just by asking about your general support for the Bill, which is outlined in the evidence. Can you just explain why you think the current law is ineffective or unclear?&#10;Speaker: Alastair Birch&#10;Content: Bore da—bore da, bawb. So, I'm Alastair Birch. The statement, really, from ADEW is that the rights of the child should be educated and achieved, really, under the United Nations Convention on the Rights of the Child. The current legislation has been criticised, obviously, by the UN concerning the defence of reasonable punishment still being within our current legislation. So, we will always—ADEW will always—advocate that the rights of the child be upheld, so that is really the fundamental aspect in terms of the statement from ADEW, and the position of ADEW is that the rights of the child are fundamental in this process. And there are certain articles—. I know that the Rights of Children and Young Persons (Wales) Measure 2011 made sure that article 3 and article" target="1. The reasonable punishment defense can undermine child protection efforts by permitting an arbitrary level of violence against children, which invades their physical integrity. This ambiguity in how children are treated may create a potential pathway to more serious physical or sexual abuse.&#10;2. Changing this aspect of the law would contribute to shifting societal attitudes towards recognizing the need for physically safe environments for all children. It would help clarify cultural perceptions and expectations around caring for and treating children appropriately.&#10;3. There is evidence that changing legislation related to physical punishment improves children's positions within their families, as it encourages positive parenting techniques and discourages harmful practices.&#10;4. The voice of the child is consistent in expressing that physical punishment is harmful and demeaning. Ensuring children feel heard and valued in discussions about their wellbeing and safety can improve educational experiences and promote empathy, resilience, and emotional intelligence among their peers.">
