y Huw David, have been consulted as key stakeholders in the legislation. They have collaborated with Welsh Government officials to ensure successful implementation of the Bill, should it be passed.&#10;&#10;3. Sally Jenkins, representing the Association of Directors of Social Services, acknowledges that while this legislation is infrequently used, its implementation will significantly impact how they care for and nurture children in Wales. Local authorities have conducted research to understand the potential impact and related costs. She suggests that successful implementation requires collaboration between various stakeholders, including education, social care, preventative services, Welsh Government, and the National Assembly, with awareness campaigns being crucial.&#10;&#10;4. Hefin David AM points out that costs associated with the legislation would not only come from an increase in referrals but also from training of staff, awareness-raising efforts, and other additional expenses.&#10;&#10;5. Sally Jenkins agrees with this assessment, noting that many of these related costs will be aligned with existing initiatives. She emphasizes the importance of understanding the trajectory of costs and cases during the implementation phase to ensure appropriate resource allocation and decision-making processes for social services and police.">
