    <edge source="1. Dawn Bowden AM, along with other agencies such as Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service Cymru and the police, has been involved in workshops for at least two years, discussing the implications of the Bill on their agencies and potential trajectories for referral into their services. They have also had extensive discussions with CAFCASS Cymru regarding the impact on private law cases and any fallout that could affect children's services, taking into account the pressures these services are already facing. Dawn Bowden AM has been committed to working closely with Welsh Government officials throughout this process and intends to continue doing so.&#10;2. Huw David mentioned that local authorities have been consulted as key stakeholders, and their officials have collaborated with Welsh Government officials to ensure the successful implementation of the Bill, should it be passed.&#10;3. Sally Jenkins, representing the Association of Directors of Social Services, has had involvement in this area for over two years and welcomed the clarity that this Bill would bring, not only for children and parents but also for professionals. She recognizes that although this legislation is infrequently used, its implementation will significantly impact how they care for and nurture children in Wales, providing much-needed clarity. Local authorities have conducted some research to understand the potential impact and related costs, and further work is needed during the implementation phase." target="1. Increased referrals to children's services: While it is not anticipated that there will be a huge increase in referrals, some rise in reports related to child smacking may still occur due to increased awareness and understanding of the legislation.&#10;&#10;2. Training of staff: Implementing the new law would require training for relevant personnel within local authorities, social services, CAFCASS Cymru, police, and third-party organizations. This includes ensuring that staff understands the implications of the Bill, how it changes their roles and responsibilities, and how to respond appropriately to reports or allegations related to child smacking.&#10;&#10;3. Awareness campaigns: Raising public awareness about the new law is crucial to ensure families do not feel criminalized and understand the reporting mechanisms. This would involve designing and executing awareness campaigns targeting various stakeholders, including parents, schools, healthcare providers, and community organizations. These campaigns can incur significant costs related to marketing materials, event organization, and personnel time.&#10;&#10;4. Collaborative work between agencies: Successful implementation of the Bill will require close collaboration between local authorities, Welsh Government, social services, police, CAFCASS Cymru, and third-party organizations involved in preventative services. This may involve additional expenses related to meetings, consultations, and coordination efforts.&#10;&#10;5. Cost trajectory: Understanding the cost implications during the implementation phase is essential for appropriate resource allocation and decision-making processes. This includes monitoring the number of referrals and cases, associated costs, and ensuring that resources are distributed proportionately between agencies involved in implementing the new law.&#10;&#10;6. Related costs aligned with existing initiatives: Many expenses related to staff training and awareness campaigns may be partially offset by aligning them with existing initiatives. However, this would still require significant time and effort to coordinate efforts across various stakeholders.&#10;&#10;7. Ongoing evaluation and assessment: Ensuring that the new law is effectively implemented will require ongoing monitoring and assessment of its impact on children, families, and agencies involved in implementing the legislation. This may involve additional costs related to data collection, analysis, and reporting.">
