    <edge source="1. Dawn Bowden AM, along with other agencies such as Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service Cymru and the police, has been involved in workshops for at least two years, discussing the implications of the Bill on their agencies and potential trajectories for referral into their services. They have also had extensive discussions with CAFCASS Cymru regarding the impact on private law cases and any fallout that could affect children's services, taking into account the pressures these services are already facing. Dawn Bowden AM has been committed to working closely with Welsh Government officials throughout this process and intends to continue doing so.&#10;2. Huw David mentioned that local authorities have been consulted as key stakeholders, and their officials have collaborated with Welsh Government officials to ensure the successful implementation of the Bill, should it be passed.&#10;3. Sally Jenkins, representing the Association of Directors of Social Services, has had involvement in this area for over two years and welcomed the clarity that this Bill would bring, not only for children and parents but also for professionals. She recognizes that although this legislation is infrequently used, its implementation will significantly impact how they care for and nurture children in Wales, providing much-needed clarity. Local authorities have conducted some research to understand the potential impact and related costs, and further work is needed during the implementation phase." target="1. Over the first six months to a year, costs related to the implementation of the proposed legislation are expected to rise due to increased awareness and understanding of the new law. These costs will not only come from an increase in referrals but also from additional expenses such as training of staff, awareness-raising efforts, and other related costs.&#10;&#10;2. During this period, local authorities, Welsh Government, social services, police, CAFCASS Cymru, and third-party organizations involved in preventative services will collaborate to ensure successful implementation. They will monitor the number of referrals and cases, associated costs, and ensure that resources are distributed proportionately between agencies involved in implementing the new law.&#10;&#10;3. Some of these related costs may be aligned with existing initiatives, helping offset some expenses. However, significant time and effort will still be required to coordinate efforts across various stakeholders.&#10;&#10;4. As Dawn Bowden AM mentioned, there could be a &quot;double impact&quot; on Wales due to the culture shift brought about by the new legislation – an increase in referrals because of increased awareness and more parents seeking support services. This potential dual effect will need to be considered when evaluating the trajectory of costs during implementation.&#10;&#10;5. Over the first six months and 12 months, ongoing monitoring and assessment will help provide a clearer understanding of these costs as agencies work together to ensure families do not feel criminalized and children's rights are upheld within Welsh society.">
