    <edge source="1. Determining the threshold for child abuse: The exact threshold for child abuse is not explicitly stated in the transcript, but it is mentioned that if there is a suspicion of significant harm or neglect to the child, a referral should be made to the child care assessment team or the police. This determination is best left to the professionals who have multi-agency awareness and can assess the situation thoroughly.&#10;2. Making parents and vulnerable children aware of the line: While it may not be possible to explicitly define the threshold for everyone, increasing awareness about available support programs and resources can help both parents and vulnerable children. This includes educating professionals in schools to recognize signs of significant harm and make appropriate referrals. For vulnerable children, campaigns should be launched to inform them about resources like Childline, where they can seek help and ask questions about what constitutes acceptable behavior towards them.&#10;3. Preventing criminalization of parents: The speakers emphasize that the aim is not to criminalize parents who are bringing up their children. Instead, support programs should be made available for families facing significant problems, even if they don't meet the threshold for child abuse or neglect intervention. This approach encourages early intervention and prevention efforts while minimizing unnecessary involvement in families' lives." target=" it's okay, that they can smack their child and that that's acceptable. They don't know the difference. A young child is not going to know that difference and there is confusion about what is—. And if you asked most parents, and in fact lots of professionals, they would not be able to tell you, and probably most of you wouldn't be able to tell me exactly where is the threshold—&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Yes, where's that line.&#10;Speaker: Huw David&#10;Content: Well, at the moment, we don't know where that line is. That vulnerable child, at home, being abused by their parents, does not know where that line is. And they should know where that line is because then they can pick up the phone to Childline or they can talk to a professional and ask them where that line is. So, that would be a step forward. I do recognise, though, that what we don't want to do—and the last thing any of us want to do—is criminalise parents who are bringing up their children. That is why we're saying there needs to be an emphasis on the support programmes that are available to parents. And to be clear,">
