 to provide local authorities with the necessary resources to effectively implement new legislation and support social services departments. This includes early intervention and prevention services for families facing significant challenges, as well as awareness-raising campaigns to inform vulnerable children about available resources like Childline. Training and awareness within education settings should also be prioritized to ensure that safeguarding leads have the right support and resources. Schools can potentially host preventative services or signpost parents to them.&#10;&#10;Involving local authorities, social services, the Welsh Government, families, carers, and parents in the implementation process will help ensure a successful rollout of new policies and legislation. A major awareness-raising campaign can help ensure that all parties understand the changes and are on board with the new culture and value system for children.&#10;&#10;While there may be an increase in reports of child smacking to social services departments if the proposed Bill becomes law, the focus remains on short-term support and prevention services. The aim is not to criminalize parents or subject them to long-term social services involvement for minor instances of physical punishment. However, resources must be made available to social services departments to avoid any unintended consequences of the Bill's implementation.">
