ork with them to address concerns. This approach would likely continue if the Bill becomes law. While there may be a proportionate response from social services or the police in cases where allegations of abuse are made, the aim is not to criminalize parents or subject them to long-term social services involvement for minor instances of physical punishment.&#10;&#10;The Welsh Government has committed to raising awareness about the changes and ensuring that families, carers, and parents understand the new culture and value system for children. Local authorities will work closely with relevant parties during the implementation process, focusing on early support and prevention services for families. Support services for early intervention and prevention will be available to parents and carers who may struggle with parenting, emphasizing a universal offer across Wales.&#10;&#10;It is important that resources are made available to social services departments to avoid any unintended consequences of the Bill's implementation. While there may be an increase in referrals to social services, this does not necessarily mean long-term involvement. The focus remains on short-term support and prevention services, with a commitment to maintaining trust between education settings, families, and social services.">
