    <edge source="1. Huw David, as a representative of local authorities, has had a consultative role in the implementation discussions of the Bill. He, along with other local authority officials, have worked closely with Welsh Government officials to ensure the successful implementation of the Bill. This includes discussing the implications of the Bill on local authorities and potential trajectories for referral into their services.&#10;2. From a social services perspective, Sally Jenkins from the Association of Directors of Social Services (ADSS) has been involved in this area for over two years. The ADSS has worked directly towards this point and acknowledges the significance of the Bill's implementation in clarifying how they care for and nurture children in Wales. Local authorities have researched the potential impact and related costs, with further work needed during the implementation phase.&#10;3. While Welsh Government has given a commitment to raise awareness about the Bill, Huw David suggests that having this awareness-raising aspect on the face of the Bill might not be necessary. However, he believes it would be helpful for ensuring families do not feel criminalized by the legislation. The costs associated with implementing the Bill will be identified and worked on collaboratively by local authorities and Welsh Government." target="1. Over the first six months to a year, costs related to the implementation of the proposed legislation are expected to rise due to increased awareness and understanding of the new law. These costs will not only come from an increase in referrals but also from additional expenses such as training of staff, awareness-raising efforts, and other related costs.&#10;&#10;2. During this period, local authorities, Welsh Government, social services, police, CAFCASS Cymru, and third-party organizations involved in preventative services will collaborate to ensure successful implementation. They will monitor the number of referrals and cases, associated costs, and ensure that resources are distributed proportionately between agencies involved in implementing the new law.&#10;&#10;3. Some of these related costs may be aligned with existing initiatives, helping offset some expenses. However, significant time and effort will still be required to coordinate efforts across various stakeholders.&#10;&#10;4. As Dawn Bowden AM mentioned, there could be a &quot;double impact&quot; on Wales due to the culture shift brought about by the new legislation – an increase in referrals because of increased awareness and more parents seeking support services. This potential dual effect will need to be considered when evaluating the trajectory of costs during implementation.&#10;&#10;5. Over the first six months and 12 months, ongoing monitoring and assessment will help provide a clearer understanding of these costs as agencies work together to ensure families do not feel criminalized and children's rights are upheld within Welsh society.">
