    <edge source="The various factors that have contributed to the rise in the numbers of looked-after children in Wales and England include increased austerity, which has led to reduced funding for children's services and support programs. Additionally, there has been an increased awareness of adverse childhood experiences (ACEs) in Wales, leading to a better understanding of the impact of factors such as domestic abuse on children and a greater emphasis on their protection. Changes in practice with judiciary colleagues and the police service, as well as changes in preventative services, have also contributed to this rise. These factors, combined with a huge amount of work being done across local authorities and Welsh Government to address and understand the issue, aim to reduce the number of children coming into care while improving outcomes for those who are already in care." target="1. The transcript suggests that there may not be sufficient resources and services like Families First in local governments to prevent harm and support families, as speakers have expressed concerns about increased pressures on social services and reductions in funding for children's services. It is crucial to invest more in prevention programs, as early intervention can help address issues before they escalate and require more intensive (and costly) interventions.&#10;2. To mitigate these concerns, it is recommended to provide local authorities with the necessary resources to effectively implement new legislation and support social services departments. This includes early intervention and prevention services for families facing significant challenges, as well as awareness-raising campaigns to inform vulnerable children about available resources like Childline.&#10;3. Additionally, training and awareness within education settings should be prioritized to ensure that safeguarding leads have the right support and resources. Schools can also play a role in signposting parents to preventative services and potentially hosting such programs.&#10;4. To ensure successful implementation of new policies and legislation, it is essential to involve local authorities, social services, the Welsh Government, families, carers, and parents in the process. A major awareness-raising campaign can help ensure that all parties understand the changes and are on board with the new culture and value system for children.">
