    <edge source="The various factors that have contributed to the rise in the numbers of looked-after children in Wales and England include increased austerity, which has led to reduced funding for children's services and support programs. Additionally, there has been an increased awareness of adverse childhood experiences (ACEs) in Wales, leading to a better understanding of the impact of factors such as domestic abuse on children and a greater emphasis on their protection. Changes in practice with judiciary colleagues and the police service, as well as changes in preventative services, have also contributed to this rise. These factors, combined with a huge amount of work being done across local authorities and Welsh Government to address and understand the issue, aim to reduce the number of children coming into care while improving outcomes for those who are already in care." target="1. When social services professionals in Wales receive a report of domestic abuse involving a child who has been smacked, they would look into it, particularly if there are signs of harm or something clearly wrong. This assessment is carried out irrespective of the Social Services and Well-being (Wales) Act 2014.&#10;2. Before the implementation of this act, social services might not have taken action on some reports involving a child being smacked, especially if the perceived level of harm was below the threshold for intervention. This approach aligns with the historical view that reasonable chastisement is an acceptable form of discipline.&#10;3. With the Social Services and Well-being (Wales) Act 2014, social services professionals now have a more defined framework to assess reports of domestic abuse or harm to children. While this does not necessarily mean that all reported cases of smacking will result in intervention, it emphasizes a more rigorous assessment process.&#10;4. The increased clarity in training for various professions related to child protection, safeguarding, adverse childhood experiences (ACEs), and trauma-informed approaches aims to empower educational professionals and create a clear message for all professionals working with children. This commitment focuses on children's rights and well-being rather than leveraging additional money for social services.&#10;5. The primary aim of the proposed Bill is not to criminalize parents but to improve children's positions within their families and shift societal attitudes towards physical punishment. The focus is on support programs available to parents and discouraging long-term involvement from social services in family matters.">
