    <edge source="Based on the transcript, Alastair Birch expressed confidence that teachers and other educational professionals would be clear about their duty to support the implementation of the Bill. He mentioned that the training requirements for all professionals in education settings are clear, with a universal tier 1 training that emphasizes the duty to report. He also noted that 'Keeping learners safe', which serves as the bible for education professionals, stresses the responsibility on the professional to make referrals and for that universal service.&#10;&#10;However, Alastair Birch also acknowledged the need for clarity in terms of making sure that safeguarding leads within all schools have the right training and support. He mentioned the necessity of working closely with social care colleagues and other services like housing and education to ensure effective implementation.&#10;&#10;Regarding the thresholds for social care and the responsibility to make referrals, Alastair Birch emphasized that if a professional believes there is significant harm to a child, they are under a duty to report it to social care. He acknowledged the importance of maintaining trust while fulfilling this duty, noting that most referrals are made with parental consent and that professionals need to work together to ensure the best outcomes for children and families." target="1. Potential risks and concerns include:&#10;   a) Increased referrals might cause potential harm to relationships and create mistrust between educators and parents.&#10;   b) There is a risk of criminalizing parents, which could lead to further strain on families already facing significant challenges.&#10;   c) Overstretched social services departments may struggle to handle the increased number of referrals effectively.&#10;&#10;2. Mitigation strategies include:&#10;   a) Ensuring that professionals are aware of their responsibilities and feel confident in making necessary referrals when significant harm or neglect is suspected, while also building trust with parents by working daily to engage and support families.&#10;   b) Providing early intervention and prevention services for families who may struggle with parenting, encouraging a universal offer across Wales so that every parent has access to this support.&#10;   c) Launching campaigns to inform vulnerable children about resources like Childline, where they can seek help and ask questions about what constitutes acceptable behavior towards them.&#10;   d) Making local authorities, social services, and the Welsh Government fully involved in the implementation process with a major awareness-raising campaign to ensure that families, carers, and parents understand the changes and are on board with the new culture and value system for children.&#10;   e) Ensuring that resources are made available to support social services departments in implementing the new legislation while continuing their work with high-needs children and families.&#10;   f) Focusing on training and awareness within education settings to ensure that safeguarding leads have the right training and support, and working closely with social care colleagues and other services like housing and education to ensure effective implementation.">
