    <edge source="1. Increased referrals to children's services: While it is not anticipated that there will be a huge increase in referrals, some rise in reports related to child smacking may still occur due to increased awareness and understanding of the legislation.&#10;&#10;2. Training of staff: Implementing the new law would require training for relevant personnel within local authorities, social services, CAFCASS Cymru, police, and third-party organizations. This includes ensuring that staff understands the implications of the Bill, how it changes their roles and responsibilities, and how to respond appropriately to reports or allegations related to child smacking.&#10;&#10;3. Awareness campaigns: Raising public awareness about the new law is crucial to ensure families do not feel criminalized and understand the reporting mechanisms. This would involve designing and executing awareness campaigns targeting various stakeholders, including parents, schools, healthcare providers, and community organizations. These campaigns can incur significant costs related to marketing materials, event organization, and personnel time.&#10;&#10;4. Collaborative work between agencies: Successful implementation of the Bill will require close collaboration between local authorities, Welsh Government, social services, police, CAFCASS Cymru, and third-party organizations involved in preventative services. This may involve additional expenses related to meetings, consultations, and coordination efforts.&#10;&#10;5. Cost trajectory: Understanding the cost implications during the implementation phase is essential for appropriate resource allocation and decision-making processes. This includes monitoring the number of referrals and cases, associated costs, and ensuring that resources are distributed proportionately between agencies involved in implementing the new law.&#10;&#10;6. Related costs aligned with existing initiatives: Many expenses related to staff training and awareness campaigns may be partially offset by aligning them with existing initiatives. However, this would still require significant time and effort to coordinate efforts across various stakeholders.&#10;&#10;7. Ongoing evaluation and assessment: Ensuring that the new law is effectively implemented will require ongoing monitoring and assessment of its impact on children, families, and agencies involved in implementing the legislation. This may involve additional costs related to data collection, analysis, and reporting." target="1. Over the first six months to a year, costs related to the implementation of the proposed legislation are expected to rise due to increased awareness and understanding of the new law. These costs will not only come from an increase in referrals but also from additional expenses such as training of staff, awareness-raising efforts, and other related costs.&#10;&#10;2. During this period, local authorities, Welsh Government, social services, police, CAFCASS Cymru, and third-party organizations involved in preventative services will collaborate to ensure successful implementation. They will monitor the number of referrals and cases, associated costs, and ensure that resources are distributed proportionately between agencies involved in implementing the new law.&#10;&#10;3. Some of these related costs may be aligned with existing initiatives, helping offset some expenses. However, significant time and effort will still be required to coordinate efforts across various stakeholders.&#10;&#10;4. As Dawn Bowden AM mentioned, there could be a &quot;double impact&quot; on Wales due to the culture shift brought about by the new legislation – an increase in referrals because of increased awareness and more parents seeking support services. This potential dual effect will need to be considered when evaluating the trajectory of costs during implementation.&#10;&#10;5. Over the first six months and 12 months, ongoing monitoring and assessment will help provide a clearer understanding of these costs as agencies work together to ensure families do not feel criminalized and children's rights are upheld within Welsh society.">
